Rotate Matrix (90° Clockwise) – C++
Problem

Given an n × n matrix, rotate the matrix 90 degrees clockwise in-place.

The rotation must be done without using extra space.

Example:

Input
1 2 3
4 5 6
7 8 9
Output
7 4 1
8 5 2
9 6 3
Approach

To rotate the matrix in-place, we perform two steps:

1️⃣ Reverse Each Column (Vertical Swap)

We fix the column and swap the top and bottom elements of that column.

Example:

1 2 3        7 8 9
4 5 6   →    4 5 6
7 8 9        1 2 3

Code:

for(int j = 0; j < col; j++){
    for(int i = 0; i < row/2; i++){
        int temp = matrix[i][j];
        matrix[i][j] = matrix[row-1-i][j];
        matrix[row-1-i][j] = temp;
    }
}

Explanation:

Column index j is fixed

Row indices i and row-1-i are swapped

This performs a vertical reversal of each column

2️⃣ Transpose the Matrix

Now swap elements across the main diagonal.

Example:

7 8 9        7 4 1
4 5 6   →    8 5 2
1 2 3        9 6 3

Code:

for(int i = 0; i < row; i++){
    for(int j = i + 1; j < col; j++){
        swap(matrix[i][j], matrix[j][i]);
    }
}

Explanation:

Elements matrix[i][j] and matrix[j][i] are swapped

This converts rows into columns

Complete C++ Code
class Solution {
public:
    void rotate(vector<vector<int>>& matrix) {

        int row = matrix.size();
        int col = matrix[0].size();

        // Step 1: Reverse each column
        for(int j = 0; j < col; j++){
            for(int i = 0; i < row/2; i++){
                int temp = matrix[i][j];
                matrix[i][j] = matrix[row-1-i][j];
                matrix[row-1-i][j] = temp;
            }
        }

        // Step 2: Transpose the matrix
        for(int i = 0; i < row; i++){
            for(int j = i + 1; j < col; j++){
                swap(matrix[i][j], matrix[j][i]);
            }
        }
    }
};
Complexity Analysis
Type	Complexity
Time Complexity	O(n²)
Space Complexity	O(1)

The rotation is performed in-place, so no extra memory is used.

Key Idea

Reverse Columns + Transpose = 90° Clockwise Rotation
